      <title>How Indian Outsourcer TCS Is Training A Massive 100,000 Workers In Digital Tech This Year</title>
      <description>In a colossal training initiative, India&amp;rsquo;s largest IT services firm, the Mumbai-based Tata Consultancy Services (TCS), will train 100,000 employees this year in digital technologies such as automation and artificial intelligence.&#xd;
 &#xd;
The humongous training program has been necessitated by a strong demand for new technologies from customers in key verticals like retail, financial services and life sciences. About 12.5% of TCS&amp;rsquo; revenues already accrue from digital technologies and the company added 38 new customers in the digital segment in the last quarter. Digital technologies are now the firm&amp;rsquo;s fastest-growing revenue stream and will surpass $2 billion this year.  &amp;ldquo;Given the strong pipeline and market adoption of digital services across industries, we are investing in training over 100,000 professionals this year in relevant technologies,&amp;rdquo; TCS CEO N Chandrasekaran, said in a statement on Thursday while announcing the company&amp;rsquo;s quarterly results.  In the quarter ending June 2015, TCS revenues rose 9.3% to $4.04 billion from the one year ago period and net profits grew 13% to $900 million.</description>
      <dc:creator>Saritha Rai</dc:creator>
